<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ881007-0043 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief -- Herman Miller Inc.: First-Quarter Earnings Rise After Accounting Gain </HL><SO>  </SO><CO> MLHR </CO><IN> ERN </IN><TEXT>   Herman Miller Inc., Zeeland, Mich., reported that earnings in its first quarter ended Sept. 3 rose 27% to $12.8 million, or 52 cents a share, after a $3.3 million extraordinary gain because of a change in accounting principles.    Sales rose 19% to $190.5 million. A year earlier, the furniture manufacturing and marketing company earned $10.1 million, or 41 cents a share, on sales of $160.6 million.    Herman Miller also said its backlog of unfilled orders in the first quarter was $162.5 million compared with $165.9 million a year earlier.    The company said it is in the process of restructuring its U.S. office-furniture operations. It didn't explain how it is restructuring, but said it is eliminating &quot;programs and functions which are nonessential to the future&quot; of its business.    The company said the restructuring will be completed in the current quarter and &quot;will produce an annualized savings of $11 million, the full impact of which will begin to be realized in the third and fourth quarters of this fiscal year.&quot; </TEXT></DOC>